For all transects: beach has very little micro/small debris. Most items are large and in original shape / condition. Likely brought in from other areas and currents. Wave action is small. Brick / building material under other seem to be forming / integrating into the hill behind the transect.

Debris is actually becoming part of the hill that borders the beach! Glass bottle and foamed plastic noted -- see pictures. Several pieces of driftwood were in transect. 10 - 15' + , partially submerged. Concrete slab ~ 1.5' x 1.5' and 1.5' tall. A second, very similar slab is in the next transect over.

Tide is the lowest I have seen in here - lower part of intertidal is very soft. Tried to come to site on Friday and shoreline was totally submerged. Spring tides + flooding (recent rain) = high tides even at predicted low. Photos were taken from above shoreline on friday. Photos today taken walking from higher transect #s to lower. Still a lot of Lee / Irene branches on shore.

Bucket stuck in the mud just below water line (see photo with cinderblock in foreground). Counted debris in the roots coming off of the hillside (see photo). This could be an interesting data point since we know the shoreline was inundated last week (though haven't been here since end of September)

Three large (> 30" square) blocks of rock / concrete / building material half buried @ first barrier (hillside). Several smaller pieces that probably fragmented are noted here but not counted on datasheet (n ~ 16). "Other" is about 6.5' of coated electrical wire.

Wrack line has pushed beyond the first barrier (sea grass). Only counted debris from water\'s edge to first barrier, though other items were seen past barrier. Large tree trunk enters lower (closer to water) part of transect.
Substrate is pebbles and matted leaves today. Creepy cave in transect! Looks like same sock and hat as have seen here in previous months.
large item is recorded as jug -- large blue tub about 18"x6"x6". Other metal is a tube of glue (aluminum?)
Large piece of wood and plastic bag in the surf. Wood is about 1' x 4' and has a rope attached -- is a swing. One piece of wood is lodged in the hillside. No debris in the transect
Large debris is wooden slab 1' x 6'. Note: some large pieces of debris behind first barrier: jug, pepsi can, wood. Same comb as last time sampled T20 in oct?
